00:09:21.565 --> 00:09:24.091
and you might say, "Why is it so important"

00:09:24.091 --> 00:09:32.477
"that people with disabilities have access to the
 same content, the same price, at the same time?"

00:09:32.477 --> 00:09:34.776
Well, I'll tell you why. I'll start with a great story.

00:09:34.776 --> 00:09:39.525
So, I was speaking on a 
National Public Radio show in DC.

00:09:39.525 --> 00:09:44.188
And normally, when they do shows
 on topics like assistive technology,

00:09:44.188 --> 00:09:48.559
they make sure they do live captioning on the show. Well, the live captioning wasn't working.

00:09:48.559 --> 00:09:53.034
So they did a whole radio show on assistive technology and essentially cut people who were

00:09:53.034 --> 00:09:56.733
deaf or hard of hearing out of taking part, 
out of emailing in . . .

00:09:56.733 --> 00:10:01.775
What happened is that they posted a transcript two days later of what happened on the radio show.

00:10:01.775 --> 00:10:05.862
Guess what? Two days later,
 you couldn't send emails in to ask questions.

00:10:05.862 --> 00:10:08.011
They were cut out of the show.

00:10:08.011 --> 00:10:13.483
On average, you see a three-year delay between when a technology is put in place inaccessibly

00:10:13.483 --> 00:10:14.751
and when it's made accessible.

00:10:14.751 --> 00:10:18.388
So when a company says, "Well, yup, we know
 it's not accessible, but we're going to work on it."

00:10:18.388 --> 00:10:20.824
On average, that's a three-year delay.

00:10:20.824 --> 00:10:24.994
That's a three-year advantage that
 people without disabilities will get.

00:10:24.994 --> 00:10:30.400
So you want to make sure that when you introduce any type of technology, any type of website,

00:10:30.400 --> 00:10:32.803
that you make it born accessible.

00:10:32.803 --> 00:10:38.940
One of the biggest problems is 
at universities, in high school, in middle school,

00:10:38.940 --> 00:10:44.281
when kids with print disabilities don't actually
 get their textbook in an accessible format

00:10:44.281 --> 00:10:46.548
until week eight or week nine.

00:10:46.548 --> 00:10:49.921
Guess what? How would you do without 
the textbook until week nine? Right?

00:10:49.921 --> 00:10:52.022
It puts you at a disadvantage.

00:10:52.022 --> 00:10:55.759
Think about the value of information.
 Right? It drops over time.

00:10:55.759 --> 00:10:57.661
You know, we had this big snowstorm.

00:10:57.661 --> 00:11:01.231
What happens if you got the weather alert
 or the "Please evacuate your neighborhood,"

00:11:01.231 --> 00:11:03.700
but you got it three days later.

00:11:03.700 --> 00:11:06.779
It doesn't mean anything three days later.
You've already missed out.

00:11:06.779 --> 00:11:10.698
You saw that a lot with Hurricane Katrina, 
where people with disabilities did not get

00:11:10.698 --> 00:11:13.309
the emergency information in a timely manner.

00:11:13.309 --> 00:11:16.761
So that information isn't worth anything a week later.

00:11:16.761 --> 00:11:21.419
Hey guess what, we're going to have a snowstorm, it's going to be two feet, and you found out today.

00:11:23.049 --> 00:11:24.439
I mean, it's ludicrous.

00:11:25.902 --> 00:11:32.062
So people with disabilities need access to 
the same information, the same content, right?

00:11:32.062 --> 00:11:35.065
Maybe it's in a different format, 
maybe it's large print, maybe it's Braille,

00:11:35.065 --> 00:11:38.869
but they need access to the same content,
 not different content.

00:11:38.869 --> 00:11:42.806
And guess what,
 most digital content starts out accessibly.

00:11:42.806 --> 00:11:45.042
We add the barriers.

00:11:45.042 --> 00:11:51.023
Now, a great example of why we need 
access to the same content is captioning.

00:11:51.023 --> 00:11:56.319
People who are deaf or hard of hearing want 
the same, verbatim, captioning.

00:11:56.319 --> 00:11:58.988
They don't want summarized captioning.

00:11:58.988 --> 00:12:01.605
They don't want something different.
 They want access to the same text.

00:12:01.605 --> 00:12:04.629
They can judge for themselves whether or not 
they want to read through all of it.

00:12:04.629 --> 00:12:06.130
But they don't want a summarized version.

00:12:06.130 --> 00:12:11.803
They view that very much as someone is 
taking away their right to get the real information,

00:12:11.803 --> 00:12:14.805
someone is really summarizing it 
and taking away that right.

00:12:14.805 --> 00:12:20.076
You see when you talk to companies and you say, 
"Look, the website doesn't work. It's not accessible."

00:12:20.076 --> 00:12:23.810
They say, "Oh, but it's okay. 
Use our mobile version instead."

00:12:23.810 --> 00:12:25.901
"That's accessible. The full website is not accessible."

00:12:25.901 --> 00:12:30.886
Well, guess what? The mobile version usually only has about a third of the functionality

00:12:30.886 --> 00:12:33.254
that the full website version has.

00:12:33.393 --> 00:12:37.190
Did anyone hear the big news announcement
 about Monster.com in the last few weeks

00:12:37.190 --> 00:12:39.773
and the Massachusetts Attorney General? 
Anyone hear that?

00:12:39.773 --> 00:12:45.023
No one? Oh, I was going to say—you sent me
 an email about it, so I know, I know you've heard it.

00:12:45.023 --> 00:12:48.469
So, think about this for a minute.

00:12:48.469 --> 00:12:49.906
Think about this:

00:12:49.906 --> 00:12:56.180
If you want to go to Monster.com, the big job search website, you want to find out what jobs are available,

00:12:56.180 --> 00:13:01.083
but when you go, the website's not accessible.
You can call Monster on the phone.

00:13:01.083 --> 00:13:05.521
It's not very likely that they're going to read you the
300 jobs opening, you know,

00:13:05.521 --> 00:13:07.493
that are open in your, in your area.

00:13:07.493 --> 00:13:11.127
So there was actually a settlement recently 
between Monster.com and the

00:13:11.127 --> 00:13:16.039
Massachusetts Attorney General, where they agreed to make Monster.com accessible.

00:13:16.039 --> 00:13:20.202
They agreed to make the website accessible
 because otherwise, I mean, it's ludicrous.

00:13:20.202 --> 00:13:24.226
You can't get the same content by
 calling on the phone or using a TTY.

00:13:24.226 --> 00:13:27.911
They're not going to read you 
300 job ads over the phone.

00:13:27.911 --> 00:13:34.250
So these are all really important concepts of 
same time, same content, and the same price.

00:13:34.250 --> 00:13:38.220
Have you ever called an airline and they say,
 while you're put on hold,

00:13:38.220 --> 00:13:41.725
"Lower fares may be available on our website."

00:13:41.725 --> 00:13:46.162
Well, guess what? Most people have heard that
 when you've called them, right? Guess what?

00:13:46.162 --> 00:13:50.499
If you can't use the website,
 you can't get the lowest fare.

00:13:50.499 --> 00:13:53.004
There's a great example of 
a settlement with MegaBus.

00:13:53.004 --> 00:13:57.374
The Justice Department had a settlement with MegaBus. Are you all familiar with MegaBus?

00:13:57.374 --> 00:13:59.041
You know, they're the buses that go in the northeast.

00:13:59.041 --> 00:14:03.836
They have the big signs on the back:
 "Fares low as one dollar! Website only."

00:14:03.836 --> 00:14:09.187
So guess what? You can't get the one-dollar fares. And their website wasn't accessible, so,

00:14:09.187 --> 00:14:12.689
if you couldn't use their website, 
you couldn't get the one-dollar fares.

00:14:12.689 --> 00:14:14.891
And that was part of the settlement
 with the Justice Department.

00:14:14.891 --> 00:14:21.502
When stores have web-only prices, guess what? 
If it's a web-only price, and the website doesn't work,

00:14:21.502 --> 00:14:23.567
you can't get that price.

00:14:23.567 --> 00:14:25.602
When you have to use a call center
 and get charged an extra fee,

00:14:25.602 --> 00:14:30.907
there's all these situations where really, you wind up, if you don't have access to their website,

00:14:30.907 --> 00:14:33.911
you generally get charged more.

00:14:33.911 --> 00:14:37.948
And that's why I say separate access 
to information is inherently unequal.

00:14:37.948 --> 00:14:41.652
If you look back at the Brown vs. Board of Education decision, right, and they talk about

00:14:41.652 --> 00:14:44.689
that separate schools are inherently unequal, 
well guess what?

00:14:44.689 --> 00:14:50.560
If you don't have access to the same digital content, it's inherently unequal. Okay?

00:14:50.560 --> 00:14:52.214
Regardless of where in history you look,

